    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"277611\">Todd Trimble</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/why.20graphs.20are.20not.20algebraic.3F/near/229376720\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>It's possible I made a mistake, but I thought I did extend <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span> with two points. </p>\n<p>Anyway, there are lots of ways of seeing that these examples are not Barr exact. In the case of graphs: these form a quasitopos. If it were Barr exact, then it would also be a topos, and hence balanced. But that can't possibly be right.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>So, what is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>K</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K \\times K</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.76666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span> in your example? When I  compute it, I find it is indeed <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span> extended with two points: in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>K</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K\\times K</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.76666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span> there must be 4 points and 1 arrow, since in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span> there are 2 points and 1 arrow. Am I wrong?</p>",
        "id": 229403774,
        "sender_full_name": "Ambroise",
        "timestamp": 1615251200
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ambroise, I'll probably decline to pursue this since you seem satisfied that you have an example, which is good. I'm not saying you're wrong, and there's a good chance my example was botched, but the main point I wanted to make is that there are various ways of seeing that sets equipped with a binary relation cannot possibly be Barr exact.</p>",
        "id": 229415191,
        "sender_full_name": "Todd Trimble",
        "timestamp": 1615259935
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Sure! Thanks for your help!</p>",
